{"title_page": "Paul Eddington", "text_new": "{{short description|English actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Paul Eddington \n| honorific_suffix   = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}\n| image        = Paul Eddington 2.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1927|6|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[St John's Wood]], [[London]], England\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1995|11|4|1927|6|18|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Southwark]], [[London]], England\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1940s&ndash;1995\n| spouse       = {{Marriage|Patricia Scott|1952|end=his death}}\n| children = 4\n}}\n'''Paul Clark Eddington,''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} (18 June 1927 \u2013 4 November 1995) was an English actor who appeared in the [[British sitcom|television sitcoms]] ''[[The Good Life (1975 TV series)|The Good Life]]'' and ''[[Yes Minister|Yes Minister/Yes Prime Minister]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nEddington was born in [[St John's Wood]] in London to Albert Clark Eddington and Frances Mary (n\u00e9e Roberts).<ref>Birth registered (as \"Paul Clark Eddington\") in Paddington Registration District in the third quarter of 1927. Eddington gave his place of birth as St John's Wood in a ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' interview with [[Roy Plomley]] in August 1981.</ref> The family were [[Quaker]]s, and Eddington was brought up by his parents with strict family values. He attended [[Sibford School]], [[Sibford Ferris]], [[Oxfordshire]]. In 1952, he married Patricia (n\u00e9e Scott).\n\n==Career==\nHaving registered as a [[conscientious objector]], Eddington began his acting career as a teenager with [[Entertainments National Service Association]] (ENSA) during the [[World War II|Second World War]].<ref name=\"Independent obituary\">{{cite news|last1=Benedick|first1=Adam|title=OBITUARY: Paul Eddington|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-paul-eddington-1580768.html|accessdate=12 June 2014|work=The Independent|date=7 November 1995}}</ref> He worked for a [[repertory]] theatre company in [[Sheffield]] and made his first TV appearance in 1956 as a regular cast member of ''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood (TV series)|The Adventures of Robin Hood]]''. Initially he played minor characters, but in the fourth season (1959\u201360), he played [[Will Scarlet]]. He had roles in episodes of ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'' (1963), ''[[The Prisoner]]'' (1967) and the final episode of ''[[The Champions]]'' (1969). He also had a supporting role in [[Hammer Film Productions|Hammer Films]]' ''[[The Devil Rides Out (film)|The Devil Rides Out]]'' (1968), an episode of ''[[Van der Valk]]'' in 1972, and appeared as a \"[[straight man]]\" (substituting for regular [[Stooge (comedian)|stooge]] [[Henry McGee]]) in a 1976 episode of ''[[The Benny Hill Show]]''. He also appeared in most episodes of the [[Associated Television|ATV]] series ''Hine'' (1971). In this he played Astor Harris, a member of an arms-dealing firm named Pendles. Eddington appeared as civil servant Strand in the last series of ''[[Special Branch (TV series)|Special Branch]]'' (1974).\n\n===Career peak===\nAlthough he was an actor for all his adult life, it was not until Eddington was in his late forties that he became a household name because of his role in  ''[[The Good Life (1975 TV series)|The Good Life]]'' (US: ''Good Neighbours''), first screened by the [[BBC]] in 1975,<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> and written by [[Esmonde_and_Larbey|John Esmonde and Bob Larbey]]. The sitcom focuses on a suburban couple who decide to give up conventionally paid work and become self-sufficient in their suburban garden. Eddington was cast as [[The Good Life (1975 TV series)#Jerry Leadbetter|Jerry Leadbetter]], a neighbour of the main characters, and [[Penelope Keith]] played his wife, [[Margo Leadbetter|Margo]]. Originally intended as small parts, the Leadbetters soon became essential foils for the two stars. He also appeared in a single episode of another Esmonde and Larbey sitcom, ''[[Get Some In!]]'' in 1977.\n\nEddington's profile was raised further when he played the title role of [[Jim Hacker]] in the comedy series ''[[Yes Minister]]'' (1980\u201384) and ''Yes, Prime Minister'' (1986\u201388) \u2013 said to have been [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s favourite TV programme. He was shortlisted four times for the [[BAFTA]] award for Best Light Entertainment Performance for the series, but he lost out to his co-star [[Nigel Hawthorne]] on each occasion.\n\nDuring 1987 Eddington appeared as Sir Joseph Porter in ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]'' in Australia.<ref>[http://www.essgee.com/html/PinaforeVersion.html The Pirates of HMS Pinafore] ''essgee.com'', accessed 26 May 2019</ref> His last roles included Guy Wheeler, a corrupt property developer in the ''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]'' episode ''The Wrong Goodbye'' (1989); as Richard Cuthbertson alongside ''Good Life'' co-star [[Felicity Kendal]] in the TV dramatisation of ''[[The Camomile Lawn (TV serial)|The Camomile Lawn]]'' (1992); the voice of Badger in ''The Adventures of Mole'' and [[Robert Shallow|Justice Shallow]] in ''Henry IV'' (1995); a BBC adaptation of Shakespeare's ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]]'' and ''[[Henry IV, Part 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brooke|first1=Michael|title=''Henry IV'' (1995)|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/1047838/|website=BFI Screenonline|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> He was reunited with another ''Good Life'' co-star [[Richard Briers]] in a run of the play ''[[Home (play)|Home]]'' in 1994.<ref name=\"Independent cancer\" />\n\nEddington read extracts from [[Sir Winston Churchill]]'s ''[[A History of the English-Speaking Peoples]]'' for the award-winning [[BBC Radio]] series ''[[This Sceptred Isle]]''; he died midway through the production, and his place was taken by [[Peter Jeffrey]].\n\n===Awards and honours===\nEddington was made a [[Order of the British Empire|Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the 1987 New Year Honours.<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /><ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/50764/supplements/8/page.pdf Supplement to The London Gazette, 31 December 1986, p. 8, accessed on 9 December 2013] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006223105/http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/50764/supplements/8/page.pdf |date=6 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Final years and death==\nEddington's [[autobiography]], ''So Far, So Good'', was published by [[Hodder & Stoughton]] in 1995. On 30 October 1995, five days before Eddington's death, the BBC aired an edition of ''[[Face to Face (British TV series)|Face to Face]]'' in which he discussed his life, career and battle with lymphoma.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JHIIwv3XdZk Face to Face with Jeremy Isaacs (see 1995 programme)]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SyvdAAAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22He+did+very+little+harm%22+ ''The Face on the Screen: Death, Recognition and Spectatorship''], Therese Davis, Intellect, 2004, page 19</ref> On that show he was asked how he would like to be remembered: {{Quote|text=\"A journalist once asked me what I would like my epitaph to be and I said I think I would like it to be, 'He did very little harm'. And that's not easy. Most people seem to me to do a great deal of harm. If I could be remembered as having done very little, that would suit me.\"|sign=Paul Eddington|source=''[[Face to Face (British TV series)|Face to Face]]''}}  \n\nEddington had been diagnosed with a rare form of [[cancer]], known as [[mycosis fungoides]], when he was 28. The ailment was to cause his death eventually, but in the intervening four decades, Eddington and his immediate family kept his condition private. It only became public knowledge in 1994, when Eddington responded to press speculation about his darkening skin and hair loss.<ref name=\"Independent cancer\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/actor-reveals-he-has-rare-skin-cancer-yes-minister-star-refuses-to-let-illness-remove-him-from-centrestage-ian-mackinnon-reports-1419608.html |title=Actor reveals he has rare skin cancer: 'Yes Minister' star refuses to let illness remove him from centre-stage |first=Ian |last=Mackinnon |date=1 June 1994 |newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nEddington died in [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]], London, on 4 November 1995.<ref>{{cite news | title = Tributes flow for Paul Eddington, 'a brave man and a fine actor'  | work =The Independent | date =7 November 1995 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/tributes-flow-for-paul-eddington-a-brave-man-and-a-fine-actor-1580747.html | accessdate = 2014-07-22}}</ref> He and Patricia, his wife of 43 years, had three sons and a daughter.<ref>[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who 2009]]</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''The Secret of the Forest''\n| Museum tour leader\n|\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''[[Sailor Beware! (1956 film)|Sailor Beware!]]''\n| Bearded Sailor\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''[[Jet Storm]]''\n| Victor Tracer\n|\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''[[Desert Mice]]''\n| Army Officer\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1960\n| ''The Man Who Was Nobody''\n| Franz Reuter\n|\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[Ring of Spies]]''\n| Johnnie\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[The Devil Rides Out (film)|The Devil Rides Out]]''\n| Richard Eaton\n|\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[The Amazing Mr Blunden]]''\n| Vicar\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Baxter!]]''\n| Mr. Rawling\n|\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Fall of Eagles]]''\n| [[Georgi Plekhanov|George Plekhanov]]\n| TV Mini-Series, 1 episode\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last= Eddington |first= Paul | title= So Far, So Good: The Autobiography |publisher= [[Trafalgar Square Publishing]] |date=March 1996 |isbn= 978-0-340-63837-8 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|0248844|Paul Eddington}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eddington, Paul}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:British conscientious objectors]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:Deaths from lymphoma]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English pacifists]]\n[[Category:English Quakers]]\n[[Category:Entertainments National Service Association personnel]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sibford School]]\n[[Category:British male comedy actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Paul Eddington \n| honorific_suffix   = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}}\n| image        = Paul Eddington 2.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1927|6|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[St John's Wood]], [[London]], England\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1995|11|4|1927|6|18|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Southwark]], [[London]], England\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1940s&ndash;1995\n| spouse       = {{Marriage|Patricia Scott|1952|end=his death}}\n| children = 4\n}}\n'''Paul Clark Eddington,''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} (18 June 1927 \u2013 4 November 1995) was an English actor who appeared in the [[British sitcom|television sitcoms]] ''[[The Good Life (1975 TV series)|The Good Life]]'' and ''[[Yes Minister|Yes Minister/Yes Prime Minister]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nEddington was born in [[St John's Wood]] in London to Albert Clark Eddington and Frances Mary (n\u00e9e Roberts).<ref>Birth registered (as \"Paul Clark Eddington\") in Paddington Registration District in the third quarter of 1927. Eddington gave his place of birth as St John's Wood in a ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' interview with [[Roy Plomley]] in August 1981.</ref> The family were [[Quaker]]s, and Eddington was brought up by his parents with strict family values. He attended [[Sibford School]], [[Sibford Ferris]], [[Oxfordshire]]. In 1952, he married Patricia (n\u00e9e Scott).\n\n==Career==\nHaving registered as a [[conscientious objector]], Eddington began his acting career as a teenager with [[Entertainments National Service Association]] (ENSA) during the [[World War II|Second World War]].<ref name=\"Independent obituary\">{{cite news|last1=Benedick|first1=Adam|title=OBITUARY: Paul Eddington|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-paul-eddington-1580768.html|accessdate=12 June 2014|work=The Independent|date=7 November 1995}}</ref> He worked for a [[repertory]] theatre company in [[Sheffield]] and made his first TV appearance in 1956 as a regular cast member of ''[[The Adventures of Robin Hood (TV series)|The Adventures of Robin Hood]]''. Initially he played minor characters, but in the fourth season (1959\u201360), he played [[Will Scarlet]]. He had roles in episodes of ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'' (1963), ''[[The Prisoner]]'' (1967) and the final episode of ''[[The Champions]]'' (1969). He also had a supporting role in [[Hammer Film Productions|Hammer Films]]' ''[[The Devil Rides Out (film)|The Devil Rides Out]]'' (1968), an episode of ''[[Van der Valk]]'' in 1972, and appeared as a \"[[straight man]]\" (substituting for regular [[Stooge (comedian)|stooge]] [[Henry McGee]]) in a 1976 episode of ''[[The Benny Hill Show]]''. He also appeared in most episodes of the [[Associated Television|ATV]] series ''Hine'' (1971). In this he played Astor Harris, a member of an arms-dealing firm named Pendles. Eddington appeared as civil servant Strand in the last series of ''[[Special Branch (TV series)|Special Branch]]'' (1974).\n\n===Career peak===\nAlthough he was an actor for all his adult life, it was not until Eddington was in his late forties that he became a household name because of his role in  ''[[The Good Life (1975 TV series)|The Good Life]]'' (US: ''Good Neighbours''), first screened by the [[BBC]] in 1975,<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> and written by [[Esmonde_and_Larbey|John Esmonde and Bob Larbey]]. The sitcom focuses on a suburban couple who decide to give up conventionally paid work and become self-sufficient in their suburban garden. Eddington was cast as [[The Good Life (1975 TV series)#Jerry Leadbetter|Jerry Leadbetter]], a neighbour of the main characters, and [[Penelope Keith]] played his wife, [[Margo Leadbetter|Margo]]. Originally intended as small parts, the Leadbetters soon became essential foils for the two stars. He also appeared in a single episode of another Esmonde and Larbey sitcom, ''[[Get Some In!]]'' in 1977.\n\nEddington's profile was raised further when he played the title role of [[Jim Hacker]] in the comedy series ''[[Yes Minister]]'' (1980\u201384) and ''Yes, Prime Minister'' (1986\u201388) \u2013 said to have been [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s favourite TV programme. He was shortlisted four times for the [[BAFTA]] award for Best Light Entertainment Performance for the series, but he lost out to his co-star [[Nigel Hawthorne]] on each occasion.\n\nDuring 1987 Eddington appeared as Sir Joseph Porter in ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]'' in Australia.<ref>[http://www.essgee.com/html/PinaforeVersion.html The Pirates of HMS Pinafore] ''essgee.com'', accessed 26 May 2019</ref> His last roles included Guy Wheeler, a corrupt property developer in the ''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]'' episode ''The Wrong Goodbye'' (1989); as Richard Cuthbertson alongside ''Good Life'' co-star [[Felicity Kendal]] in the TV dramatisation of ''[[The Camomile Lawn (TV serial)|The Camomile Lawn]]'' (1992); the voice of Badger in ''The Adventures of Mole'' and [[Robert Shallow|Justice Shallow]] in ''Henry IV'' (1995); a BBC adaptation of Shakespeare's ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]]'' and ''[[Henry IV, Part 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brooke|first1=Michael|title=''Henry IV'' (1995)|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/1047838/|website=BFI Screenonline|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> He was reunited with another ''Good Life'' co-star [[Richard Briers]] in a run of the play ''[[Home (play)|Home]]'' in 1994.<ref name=\"Independent cancer\" />\n\nEddington read extracts from [[Sir Winston Churchill]]'s ''[[A History of the English-Speaking Peoples]]'' for the award-winning [[BBC Radio]] series ''[[This Sceptred Isle]]'', however he died midway through the production and was succeeded by [[Peter Jeffrey]].\n\n===Awards and honours===\nEddington was made a [[Order of the British Empire|Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the 1987 New Year Honours.<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /><ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/50764/supplements/8/page.pdf Supplement to The London Gazette, 31 December 1986, p. 8, accessed on 9 December 2013] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006223105/http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/50764/supplements/8/page.pdf |date=6 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Final years and death==\nEddington's [[autobiography]], ''So Far, So Good'', was published by [[Hodder & Stoughton]] in 1995. On 30 October 1995, five days before Eddington's death, the BBC aired an edition of ''[[Face to Face (British TV series)|Face to Face]]'' in which he discussed his life, career and battle with lymphoma.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JHIIwv3XdZk Face to Face with Jeremy Isaacs (see 1995 programme)]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SyvdAAAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22He+did+very+little+harm%22+ ''The Face on the Screen: Death, Recognition and Spectatorship''], Therese Davis, Intellect, 2004, page 19</ref> On that show he was asked how he would like to be remembered: {{Quote|text=\"A journalist once asked me what I would like my epitaph to be and I said I think I would like it to be, 'He did very little harm'. And that's not easy. Most people seem to me to do a great deal of harm. If I could be remembered as having done very little, that would suit me.\"|sign=Paul Eddington|source=''[[Face to Face (British TV series)|Face to Face]]''}}  \n\nEddington had been diagnosed with a rare form of [[cancer]], known as [[mycosis fungoides]], when he was 28. The ailment was to cause his death eventually, but in the intervening four decades, Eddington and his immediate family kept his condition private. It only became public knowledge in 1994, when Eddington responded to press speculation about his darkening skin and hair loss.<ref name=\"Independent cancer\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/actor-reveals-he-has-rare-skin-cancer-yes-minister-star-refuses-to-let-illness-remove-him-from-centrestage-ian-mackinnon-reports-1419608.html |title=Actor reveals he has rare skin cancer: 'Yes Minister' star refuses to let illness remove him from centre-stage |first=Ian |last=Mackinnon |date=1 June 1994 |newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nEddington died in [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]], London, on 4 November 1995.<ref>{{cite news | title = Tributes flow for Paul Eddington, 'a brave man and a fine actor'  | work =The Independent | date =7 November 1995 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/tributes-flow-for-paul-eddington-a-brave-man-and-a-fine-actor-1580747.html | accessdate = 2014-07-22}}</ref> He and Patricia, his wife of 43 years, had three sons and a daughter.<ref>[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who 2009]]</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''The Secret of the Forest''\n| Museum tour leader\n|\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''[[Sailor Beware! (1956 film)|Sailor Beware!]]''\n| Bearded Sailor\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''[[Jet Storm]]''\n| Victor Tracer\n|\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''[[Desert Mice]]''\n| Army Officer\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1960\n| ''The Man Who Was Nobody''\n| Franz Reuter\n|\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[Ring of Spies]]''\n| Johnnie\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[The Devil Rides Out (film)|The Devil Rides Out]]''\n| Richard Eaton\n|\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[The Amazing Mr Blunden]]''\n| Vicar\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Baxter!]]''\n| Mr. Rawling\n|\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Fall of Eagles]]''\n| [[Georgi Plekhanov|George Plekhanov]]\n| TV Mini-Series, 1 episode\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last= Eddington |first= Paul | title= So Far, So Good: The Autobiography |publisher= [[Trafalgar Square Publishing]] |date=March 1996 |isbn= 978-0-340-63837-8 }}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|0248844|Paul Eddington}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eddington, Paul}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:British conscientious objectors]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:Deaths from lymphoma]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English pacifists]]\n[[Category:English Quakers]]\n[[Category:Entertainments National Service Association personnel]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sibford School]]\n[[Category:British male comedy actors]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer peak:improve wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Eddington"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Ireland", "text_new": "{{About|the coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Ireland|the pandemic in Northern Ireland|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Northern Ireland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Ireland}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ireland\n| map1            = Confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Ireland by county.webm\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases by [[Counties of Ireland|county]]\n| alt1            = \n| map2            = Confirmed cases of COVID-19 per 100k inhabitants in Ireland.webm\n| legend2         = Confirmed cases per 100k inhabitants by [[Counties of Ireland|county]]\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19)\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|Severe acute respiratory syndrome<br/>coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2)\n| source          = [[Bat]]s or possibly [[pangolin]]s<ref>{{cite journal |title=Identifying SARS-CoV-2 related coronaviruses in Malayan pangolins |journal=Nature |date=26 March 2020 |doi=10.1038/s41586-020-2169-0 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-020-2169-0_reference.pdf |accessdate=27 March 2020|last1=Lam |first1=Tommy Tsan-Yuk |last2=Shum |first2=Marcus Ho-Hin |last3=Zhu |first3=Hua-Chen |last4=Tong |first4=Yi-Gang |last5=Ni |first5=Xue-Bing |last6=Liao |first6=Yun-Shi |last7=Wei |first7=Wei |last8=Cheung |first8=William Yiu-Man |last9=Li |first9=Wen-Juan |last10=Li |first10=Lian-Feng |last11=Leung |first11=Gabriel M. |last12=Holmes |first12=Edward C. |last13=Hu |first13=Yan-Ling |last14=Guan |first14=Yi |pmid=32218527 }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO report 28 February 2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/who-china-joint-mission-on-covid-19-final-report.pdf |title=Report of the WHO-China Joint Mission on Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |date=16\u201324 February 2020 |access-date=8 March 2020 |author=WHO\u2013China Joint Mission |work=[[World Health Organization]]}}</ref><ref name=\"ia56U\">{{cite journal |title=Mystery deepens over animal source of coronavirus |journal=Nature |volume=579 |pages=18\u201319 |date=26 February 2020 |doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00548-w |pmid=32127703 |vauthors=Cyranoski D |issue=7797 |bibcode=2020Natur.579...18C|doi-access=free }}</ref>, \n| location        = [[Republic of Ireland]]\n| first_case      = [[Dublin]]\n| arrival_date    = 29 February 2020<br/>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=29|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Northern Italy]] (local)<br/>[[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]] (global)<br/>{{coord|30|35|14|N|114|17|17|E|type:adm2nd_region:CN-42}}\n| recovery_cases  = 9,233 <small>(as of 21 April 2020)</small><ref name=\"21 April\"/>\n| deaths          = 794 <small>(as of 23 April 2020)</small><ref name=\"23 April\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 17,607 <small>(as of 23 April 2020)</small><ref name=\"23 April\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.gov.ie/en/news/7e0924-latest-updates-on-covid-19-coronavirus/ Gov.ie - Latest updates on COVID-19 (Coronavirus)]\n| dates           = 8 March 2020\n}}\n\nConfirmation that the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] had spread to [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] came on 29 February 2020.<ref name=\"BBC News 1st Irish\">{{cite news |title=First case of coronavirus in Republic of Ireland |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51693259 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=29 February 2020 |accessdate=2020-03-02}}</ref> [[Tony Holohan]], the [[Chief Medical Officer (Ireland)|Chief Medical Officer]] for the [[Department of Health (Ireland)|Irish Department of Health]], announced its arrival.<ref name=\"BBC News 1st Irish\"/> By 20 March, around three weeks later, it was present in all [[Counties of Ireland|26 counties]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/coronavirus-cases-now-confirmed-in-every-county-in-ireland-1.4209389|title=Coronavirus cases now confirmed in every county in Ireland|first=Paul Cullen Health|last=Editor|website=[[The Irish Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/breakdown-county-coronavirus-ireland-5054368-Mar2020/|title=Every single county in Ireland now has at least one coronavirus case - here's a breakdown of where the virus is|first=Garreth|last=MacNamee|website=TheJournal.ie}}</ref>\n\nThe pandemic's arrival affected many aspects of society, initially including the cancellation of [[Saint Patrick's Day|St Patrick's Day]] parades and all festivals.<ref name=\"Dublin Live Pat Parade canc\"/><ref name=\"Waterford Live Pat canc\"/><ref name=\"Echo parade canc\"/><ref name=\"BBC pat parades off\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51806551|title=Irish St Patrick's Day parades off over coronavirus|date=2020-03-09|publisher=[[BBC News]] |language=en-GB |access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> [[Taoiseach]] [[Leo Varadkar]] broke from a trip to [[Washington, D.C.]], where he was meeting with [[President of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]], to announce the closure of all schools, colleges, childcare and other public facilities until at least 29 March 2020.<ref name=\"Irish Times schools to shut\"/> These [[public health]] measures were subsequently expanded and extended until at least 19 April 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/coronavirus-new-measures-5055686-Mar2020/|title=Taoiseach announces all non-essential shops to close, restrictions on gatherings of more than four people|last=Murray|first=Sean|website=[[TheJournal.ie]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Another extension carried the measures onwards until 5 May 2020 at the earliest.<ref name=\"extend\"/>\n\nOn 17 March, the [[Health Service Executive]] (HSE) launched a recruitment campaign, asking both healthcare professionals and non-healthcare professionals to \"be on call for Ireland\".<ref name=beon/> [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|D\u00e1il]] and [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]] passed [[Health (Preservation and Protection and other Emergency Measures in the Public Interest) Act 2020|an emergency bill]]\u2014giving the state power to [[Detention (imprisonment)|detain]] people, restrict travel and keep people in their homes in order to help control the virus's spread\u2014with [[President of Ireland]] [[Michael D. Higgins]] signing it into law.<ref name=\"RTE Higgins signs emerg\"/>\n\n<!-- Please also update the stats in the Europe page also https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Europe#Ireland -->\nAs of 23 April, the [[Department of Health (Ireland)|Department of Health]] has confirmed 17,607 cases and 794 deaths.<ref name=\"23 April\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2020/0423/1134432-figures-covid-thursday-23-april/|title=Covid-19: 28 more deaths, 936 additional cases|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News and Current Affairs]]|date=23 April 2020|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe surveillance of COVID-19 cases has been integrated into the existing national Computerised Infectious Disease Reporting (CIDR) system since COVID-19 was made a notifiable disease on 20 February 2020. CIDR is the information system used to manage the surveillance and control of infectious diseases in Ireland, both at regional and national level.<ref name=\"notifiable\">{{cite web|url=https://ndsc.newsweaver.ie/4otaa688p3/c2f2qexyyf210gkzp9yxn5?a=1&p=56582761&t=31302934|title=Minister for Health signs regulations to make COVID-19 a notifiable disease in Ireland|publisher=HSE [[Health Protection Surveillance Centre]] |date=1 March 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Daily epidemiological reports on COVID-19 are prepared by the [[Health Protection Surveillance Centre]] for the [[National Public Health Emergency Team]] (NPHET).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.ie/en/news/7e0924-latest-updates-on-covid-19-coronavirus/|title=Latest updates on COVID-19 (Coronavirus)|publisher=[[Department of Health]] |date=10 April 2020|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n{{Side box\n |metadata=No<!--The value 'No' apparently makes the box display on the mobile site-->\n | position = left<!--To align with the other graphs on the page.-->\n | above = '''Confirmed COVID-19 Cases'''\n|abovestyle=text-align:center|text={{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=2\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|colors=#FF4500,#7a7677,#f1f527,lightblue\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-60\n|x=29 Feb,1 Mar,2 Mar,3 Mar,4 Mar,5 Mar,6 Mar,7 Mar,8 Mar,9 Mar,10 Mar,11 Mar,12 Mar,13 Mar,14 Mar,15 Mar,16 Mar,17 Mar,18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar,21 Mar,22 Mar,23 Mar,24 Mar,25 Mar,26 Mar,27 Mar,28 Mar,29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar,1 Apr,2 Apr,3 Apr,4 Apr,5 Apr,6 Apr,7 Apr,8 Apr,9 Apr,10 Apr,11 Apr,12 Apr,13 Apr,14 Apr,15 Apr, 16 Apr,17 Apr,18 Apr,19 Apr,20 Apr,21 Apr,22 Apr,23 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=Cases\n|y1Title=Total confirmed cases\n|y1=1,1,1,2,6,13,18,19,21,24,34,43,70,90,129,169,223,292,366,557,683,785,906,1125,1329,1564,1819,2121,2415,2615,2910,3235,3447,3849,4273,4604,4994,5364,5709,6074,6574,8089,8928,9655,10647,11479,12547,13271,13980,14758,15251,15652,16040,16671,17607\n|y2=,,,,,,,,,,,1,1,1,2,2,2,2,2,3,3,3,4,6,7,9,19,22,36,46,54,71,85,98,120,137,158,174,210,235,263,288,320,334,365,406,444,486,530,571,610,687,730,769,794\n|y3=,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,59,84,114,147,159,208,247,283,321,375,445,506,578,674,752,841,948,1084,1163,1263,1388,1568,1765,1949,2141,2312,2489,2707,2872,3090,3347,3578,3788,4009,4180,4393,4545\n|y4=,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,77,,,,,9233,,9233\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n{{legend|#FF4500|Total Confirmed Cases.\n{{legend|#f1f527|Total Healthcare Worker Confirmed Cases.\n{{legend|lightblue|Total Recoveries.\n{{legend|#7a7677|Total Deaths.\n}}}}}}\n}}}}\n\n{{Side box\n |metadata=No<!--The value 'No' apparently makes the box display on the mobile 