ite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/stay-indoors-im-young-sporty-and-fit-i-never-would-have-thought-id-catch-coronavirus-39070693.html|title='Stay indoors, I'm young, sporty and fit, I never would have thought I'd catch coronavirus'|first=Catherine|last=Fegan|date=24 March 2020|work=[[Irish Independent]]}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/inside-the-government-s-battle-against-coronavirus-1.4214021|title=Inside the Government's battle against coronavirus: Working under unparalleled pressure, Irish officials are facing the crisis with trepidation|first=Pat|last=Leahy|date=28 March 2020|work=[[The Irish Times]]}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.hse.ie/eng/services/news/newsfeatures/covid19-updates/ COVID-19 updates] from the [[Health Service Executive]] (HSE)\n* [https://twitter.com/McConnellDaniel/status/1234176646686609415/photo/1 Letter sent to parents of those attending Scoil Chaitr\u00edona]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Ireland| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Ireland]]\n[[Category:2020 in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Ireland]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Ireland]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ireland|Republic]]\n", "name_user": "Bygmester", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_Republic_of_Ireland"}
{"title_page": "Kenneth H. Cooper", "text_new": "'''Kenneth H. Lombrico''' (born March 4, 1931, [[Oklahoma City]])<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cooperaerobics.com/About/Our-Leaders/Kenneth-H-Cooper,-MD,-MPH.aspx |title= Kenneth Cooper, MD, MPH|publisher= Cooper Aerobics Center |quote= Born March 4, 1931, in Oklahoma City}}</ref> is a [[doctor of medicine]] and former [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] from Oklahoma, who pioneered the benefits of doing [[aerobic exercise]] for maintaining and improving health.<ref>{{cite book|author=David Levinson, Karen Christensen MacKey|title=Encyclopedia of World Sport: From Ancient Times to the Present|volume=|pages=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q8NMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=Dr.+Kenneth+Cooper+published+Aerobics&source=bl&ots=PQce2GEQxB&sig=pkRgMDfwiLe6rwJntHjydGHYhaE&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiLpoGz7LvUAhViLcAKHdB6Cj44FBDoAQgwMAI#v=onepage&q=Dr.%20Kenneth%20Cooper%20published%20Aerobics&f=false|year= 1999 |publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-195-13195-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Sport in American culture: from Ali to X-games |last=Duncan |first=Joyce |page=6 |year=2004 |publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]] |isbn=978-1-57607-024-6 }}</ref> He is the author of the 1968 book ''Aerobics'',<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/mar/30/health/he-aerobics30|work=[[latimes.com]]|title=Dr. Kenneth Cooper got a nation moving through aerobics. More than 40 years ago, his book touted a new type of exercise|first=Deborah|last=Netburn|authorlink=|date=30 March 2009|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1= Cooper |first1= Kenneth H. |title= Aerobics |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=lzxxbhuKCxgC&dq=editions:2AhzqbwhuU8C |edition= revised |volume= 14490 |date= January 1969 |origyear= 1968 |publisher= [[Bantam Books]] |isbn= 978-0-553-14490-1 |lay-url= https://www.amazon.com/review/R3RVD8L07A7QHA/ref=cm_cr_rdp_perm |laydate= 2007-12-28 }}</ref> which emphasized a point system for improving the [[cardiovascular system]]. The popular mass market version was ''The New Aerobics'' ({{ISBN|0-553-26874-0}}), published ten years later. His points system is also the basis of the 10,000 steps per day method of maintaining adequate fitness by walking.{{fact|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Career==\nA native of Oklahoma City, Cooper completed a 13-year military career. During his Air Force career, he devised a simple test (the [[Cooper test]], originally the distance run in 12 minutes) which correlated well with the existing concept of [[VO2max]], and so could conveniently be used to quickly establish the fitness level of large numbers of people. He left the Air Force in 1970, when he and his wife, Millie, moved to Dallas to found the Cooper Aerobics Center.\n\nCooper developed the Smart Snack Ribbon guidelines put into use by the convenient fun foods division of PepsiCo, Inc., Frito-Lay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fritolay.com/about-us/press-release-20030805.html|title=Snacking Now Made Easier with Frito-Lay's New Smart Snack Ribbon Label}}</ref>\n\nCooper is the founder of the non-profit research and education organization, The Cooper Institute, which was opened in 1970. Cooper is also the founder of and Chairman at the Cooper Aerobics Center in Dallas and McKinney, Texas, which comprises eight health and wellness entities.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/12/garden/at-work-with-dr-kenneth-h-cooper-the-fit-commandment.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[nytimes.com]]|title=At Work With: Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper; The Fit Commandment|first=Elaine|last= Louie|authorlink=|date=12 July 1995|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> \n\nCooper has published 18 books that have sold 30 million copies and been translated into 41 languages. Cooper encouraged millions into being active and helped to launch modern [[fitness culture]]. He is now known as the \"father of aerobics\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/news/press-releases/aerobics-kenneth-cooper-to-receive-harvard-healthy-cup-award/|title=\u201cFather of Aerobics\u201d Kenneth Cooper, MD, MPH to receive Healthy Cup Award from Harvard School of Public Health|date=2008-04-16|work=News|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.clubindustry.com/forprofits/dr-kenneth-cooper-and-how-he-became-known-father-aerobics|title=Dr. Kenneth Cooper and How He Became Known as the Father of Aerobics|date=2008-09-01|work=Club Industry|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\nHe and his wife are parents of a son and daughter. Cooper has written about the importance of [[Christianity|Christian]] religious faith in his life.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.churchfitness.com/2014/09/faith-and-fitness-interviews-the-father-of-aerobics/|title=Faith and Fitness Magazine Interviews the Father of Aerobics: Does Faith Based Fitness Make Sense Today|last=|first=|date=|work=churchfitness.com|accessdate=13 June 2017|authorlink=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iZbmltHB3_8C&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119&dq=Dr.+Kenneth+H.+Cooper+Christian+religious&source=bl&ots=qDvsmbRLO7&sig=jvXBAMI_5ZGfY2gQ5ZcYhRetR2w&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQ-c3g6LvUAhUkDsAKHYRwCu0Q6AEIaTAJ#v=onepage&q=Dr.%20Kenneth%20H.%20Cooper%20Christian%20religious&f=false|title=A Practical and Spiritual Guide to Personal Healing: A Mind, Body, Spirit Approach|author=James MacKey|publisher=iUniverse|year=2009|isbn=978-0-595-45595-9|volume=|pages=119}}</ref>\n\n== Ideas on exercise and training effect ==\nCooper studied the effect of exercise in the late 1960s and used the term \"training effect\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The aerobics program for total well-being: Exercise, diet, and emotional balance|last1=Cooper|first1=K.|publisher=Bantam|year=1985}}{{page needed|date=October 2014}}{{Dubious|Dubious|date=December 2009}}</ref> although that term had been used before.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GLYVAAAAIAAJ&q=%22training+effect%22&dq=%22training+effect%22&lr=&redir_esc=y&hl=en|title=Proceedings [of The] Annual Meeting|last=(U.S.)|first=National College Physical Education Association for Men|date=1959|publisher=Office of Publications Services, University of Illinois at Chicago Circle|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qYc2AAAAIAAJ&q=%22training+effect%22&dq=%22training+effect%22&lr=&redir_esc=y|title=Perceptual and Motor Skills|date=1959|publisher=Perceptual and Motor Skills|language=en}}</ref> The measured effects were that muscles of respiration were strengthened, the heart was strengthened, blood pressure was sometimes lowered and the total amount of blood and number of red blood cells increased, making the blood a more efficient carrier of oxygen. [[VO2 Max|VO<sub>2</sub> Max]] was increased.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} He published his ideas in a book, \"''Aerobics''\" in 1968.\n\nThe exercise necessary can be accomplished by any [[aerobic exercise]] in a wide variety of schedules - Cooper found it best to award \"points\" for each amount of exercise<ref>{{cite book|title=Aerobics|last1=Cooper|first1=Kenneth H.|year=1981|isbn=978-0-553-20992-1}}{{page needed|date=October 2014}}</ref> and require 30 points a week to maintain the Training Effect.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nCooper instead recommended a \"12-minute test\" (the [[Cooper test]]) followed by adherence to the appropriate starting-up schedule in his book. As always, he recommends that a physical exam should precede any exercise program.\n\nThe physiological effects of training have received much further study since Cooper's original work. It is now generally considered that effects of exercise on general metabolic rate ([[Excess post-exercise oxygen consumption|post-exercise]]) are comparatively small and the greatest effect occurs for only a few hours. Though endurance training does increase the VO<sub>2</sub> max of many people, there is considerable variation in the degree to which it increases VO<sub>2</sub> max between individuals.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bouchard|first1=Claude|last2=An|first2=Ping|last3=Rice|first3=Treva|last4=Skinner|first4=James S.|last5=Wilmore|first5=Jack H.|last6=Gagnon|first6=Jacques|last7=P\u00e9russe|first7=Louis|last8=Leon|first8=Arthur S.|last9=Rao|first9=D. C.|date=September 1999|title=Familial aggregation of V\u0307O<sub>2max</sub> response to exercise training: results from the HERITAGE Family Study|url=http://jap.physiology.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=10484570|journal=Journal of Applied Physiology|volume=87|issue=3|pages=1003\u20138|pmid=10484570}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Aerobics (1968)\n*Run for Your Life: Aerobic Conditioning for Your Heart (1974)\n*The Aerobics Way: New Data on the World's Most Popular Exercise Program (1978)\n*The New Aerobics (1979)\n*Aerobics for Women (1982)\n*The Aerobics Program for Total Well-being: Exercise, Diet, Emotional Balance (1982, 1983)\n*Fitness for Life, 6 Audio Cassettes (1983)\n*Aerobics Program (1985)\n*Running Without Fear (1986)\n*The New Aerobics for Women (1988)\n*Preventing Osteoporosis: Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper's Preventive Medicine Program (1989)\n*Controlling Cholesterol: Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper's Preventative Medicine Program (1989)\n*Reducing Cholesterol: A Heart-Smart Guide to Low-Fat Eating (No Nonsense Health Guide) (1989)\n*Overcoming Hypertension: Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper's Preventive Medicine Program (1990)\n*Kid Fitness: a Complete Shape-up Program From Birth Through High School (1991)\n*Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper's Antioxidant Revolution (1994)\n*Its Better To Believe (1995)\n*Faith-based Fitness The Medical Program That Uses Spiritual Motivation To Achieve Maximum Health And *Add Years To Your Life (1997)\n*Antioxidant Revolution (1997)\n*Can Stress Heal? Converting A Major Health Hazard Into A Surprising Health Benefit (1998)\n*Advanced Nutritional Therapies (1998)\n*Regaining the Power of Youth at Any Age (1998)\n*Discoveries (1999)\n*Controlling Cholesterol the Natural Way Eat Your Way to Better Health With New Breakthrough Food\n*Matters of the Heart: Adventures in Sports Medicine (2007)\n*Start Strong, Finish Strong (2007)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Aerobics]]\n*[[Bill Orban]]\n*[[Exercise]]\n*[[Exercise physiology]]\n*[[Training effect]]\n*[[Physical fitness]]\n* [[Power walking]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cooperaerobics.com/ Cooper Aerobics Center]\n*[http://www.cooperaerobics.com/About/Our-Leaders/Kenneth-H-Cooper,-MD,-MPH.aspx/ Kenneth H. Cooper Biography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Kenneth H}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American military doctors]]\n[[Category:American Christian writers]]\n[[Category:American exercise and fitness writers]]\n[[Category:Exercise instructors]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n", "text_old": "'''Kenneth H. Cooper''' (born March 4, 1931, [[Oklahoma City]])<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cooperaerobics.com/About/Our-Leaders/Kenneth-H-Cooper,-MD,-MPH.aspx |title= Kenneth Cooper, MD, MPH|publisher= Cooper Aerobics Center |quote= Born March 4, 1931, in Oklahoma City}}</ref> is a [[doctor of medicine]] and former [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] from Oklahoma, who pioneered the benefits of doing [[aerobic exercise]] for maintaining and improving health.<ref>{{cite book|author=David Levinson, Karen Christensen MacKey|title=Encyclopedia of World Sport: From Ancient Times to the Present|volume=|pages=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q8NMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=Dr.+Kenneth+Cooper+published+Aerobics&source=bl&ots=PQce2GEQxB&sig=pkRgMDfwiLe6rwJntHjydGHYhaE&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiLpoGz7LvUAhViLcAKHdB6Cj44FBDoAQgwMAI#v=onepage&q=Dr.%20Kenneth%20Cooper%20published%20Aerobics&f=false|year= 1999 |publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-195-13195-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Sport in American culture: from Ali to X-games |last=Duncan |first=Joyce |page=6 |year=2004 |publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]] |isbn=978-1-57607-024-6 }}</ref> He is the author of the 1968 book ''Aerobics'',<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/mar/30/health/he-aerobics30|work=[[latimes.com]]|title=Dr. Kenneth Cooper got a nation moving through aerobics. More than 40 years ago, his book touted a new type of exercise|first=Deborah|last=Netburn|authorlink=|date=30 March 2009|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1= Cooper |first1= Kenneth H. |title= Aerobics |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=lzxxbhuKCxgC&dq=editions:2AhzqbwhuU8C |edition= revised |volume= 14490 |date= January 1969 |origyear= 1968 |publisher= [[Bantam Books]] |isbn= 978-0-553-14490-1 |lay-url= https://www.amazon.com/review/R3RVD8L07A7QHA/ref=cm_cr_rdp_perm |laydate= 2007-12-28 }}</ref> which emphasized a point system for improving the [[cardiovascular system]]. The popular mass market version was ''The New Aerobics'' ({{ISBN|0-553-26874-0}}), published ten years later. His points system is also the basis of the 10,000 steps per day method of maintaining adequate fitness by walking.{{fact|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Career==\nA native of Oklahoma City, Cooper completed a 13-year military career. During his Air Force career, he devised a simple test (the [[Cooper test]], originally the distance run in 12 minutes) which correlated well with the existing concept of [[VO2max]], and so could conveniently be used to quickly establish the fitness level of large numbers of people. He left the Air Force in 1970, when he and his wife, Millie, moved to Dallas to found the Cooper Aerobics Center.\n\nCooper developed the Smart Snack Ribbon guidelines put into use by the convenient fun foods division of PepsiCo, Inc., Frito-Lay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fritolay.com/about-us/press-release-20030805.html|title=Snacking Now Made Easier with Frito-Lay's New Smart Snack Ribbon Label}}</ref>\n\nCooper is the founder of the non-profit research and education organization, The Cooper Institute, which was opened in 1970. Cooper is also the founder of and Chairman at the Cooper Aerobics Center in Dallas and McKinney, Texas, which comprises eight health and wellness entities.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/07/12/garden/at-work-with-dr-kenneth-h-cooper-the-fit-commandment.html?pagewanted=all|work=[[nytimes.com]]|title=At Work With: Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper; The Fit Commandment|first=Elaine|last= Louie|authorlink=|date=12 July 1995|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> \n\nCooper has published 18 books that have sold 30 million copies and been translated into 41 languages. Cooper encouraged millions into being active and helped to launch modern [[fitness culture]]. He is now known as the \"father of aerobics\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/news/press-releases/aerobics-kenneth-cooper-to-receive-harvard-healthy-cup-award/|title=\u201cFather of Aerobics\u201d Kenneth Cooper, MD, MPH to receive Healthy Cup Award from Harvard School of Public Health|date=2008-04-16|work=News|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.clubindustry.com/forprofits/dr-kenneth-cooper-and-how-he-became-known-father-aerobics|title=Dr. Kenneth Cooper and How He Became Known as the Father of Aerobics|date=2008-09-01|work=Club Industry|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\nHe and his wife are parents of a son and daughter. Cooper has written about the importance of [[Christianity|Christian]] religious faith in his life.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.churchfitness.com/2014/09/faith-and-fitness-interviews-the-father-of-aerobics/|title=Faith and Fitness Magazine Interviews the Father of Aerobics: Does Faith Based Fitness Make Sense Today|last=|first=|date=|work=churchfitness.com|accessdate=13 June 2017|authorlink=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iZbmltHB3_8C&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119&dq=Dr.+Kenneth+H.+Cooper+Christian+religious&source=bl&ots=qDvsmbRLO7&sig=jvXBAMI_5ZGfY2gQ5ZcYhRetR2w&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQ-c3g6LvUAhUkDsAKHYRwCu0Q6AEIaTAJ#v=onepage&q=Dr.%20Kenneth%20H.%20Cooper%20Christian%20religious&f=false|title=A Practical and Spiritual Guide to Personal Healing: A Mind, Body, Spirit Approach|author=James MacKey|publisher=iUniverse|year=2009|isbn=978-0-595-45595-9|volume=|pages=119}}</ref>\n\n== Ideas on exercise and training effect ==\nCooper studied the effect of exercise in the late 1960s and used the term \"training effect\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The aerobics program for total well-being: Exercise, diet, and emotional balance|last1=Cooper|first1=K.|publisher=Bantam|year=1985}}{{page needed|date=October 2014}}{{Dubious|Dubious|date=December 2009}}</ref> although that term had been used before.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GLYVAAAAIAAJ&q=%22training+effect%22&dq=%22training+effect%22&lr=&redir_esc=y&hl=en|title=Proceedings [of The] Annual Meeting|last=(U.S.)|first=National College Physical Education Association for Men|date=1959|publisher=Office of Publications Services, University of Illinois at Chicago Circle|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qYc2AAAAIAAJ&q=%22training+effect%22&dq=%22training+effect%22&lr=&redir_esc=y|title=Perceptual and Motor Skills|date=1959|publisher=Perceptual and Motor Skills|language=en}}</ref> The measured effects were that muscles of respiration were strengthened, the heart was strengthened, blood pressure was sometimes lowered and the total amount of blood and number of red blood cells increased, making the blood a more efficient carrier of oxygen. [[VO2 Max|VO<sub>2</sub> Max]] was increased.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} He published his ideas in a book, \"''Aerobics''\" in 1968.\n\nThe exercise necessary can be accomplished by any [[aerobic exercise]] in a wide variety of schedules - Cooper found it best to award \"points\" for each amount of exercise<ref>{{cite book|title=Aerobics|last1=Cooper|first1=Kenneth H.|year=1981|isbn=978-0-553-20992-1}}{{page needed|date=October 2014}}</ref> and require 30 points a week to maintain the Training Effect.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nCooper instead recommended a \"12-minute test\" (the [[Cooper test]]) followed by adherence to the appropriate starting-up schedule in his book. As always, he recommends that a physical exam should precede any exercise program.\n\nThe physiological effects of training have received much further study since Cooper's original work. It is now generally considered that effects of exercise on general metabolic rate ([[Excess post-exercise oxygen consumption|post-exercise]]) are comparatively small and the greatest effect occurs for only a few hours. Though endurance training does increase the VO<sub>2</sub> max of many people, there is considerable variation in the degree to which it increases VO<sub>2</sub> max between individuals.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bouchard|first1=Claude|last2=An|first2=Ping|last3=Rice|first3=Treva|last4=Skinner|first4=James S.|last5=Wilmore|first5=Jack H.|last6=Gagnon|first6=Jacques|last7=P\u00e9russe|first7=Louis|last8=Leon|first8=Arthur S.|last9=Rao|first9=D. C.|date=September 1999|title=Familial aggregation of V\u0307O<sub>2max</sub> response to exercise training: results from the HERITAGE Family Study|url=http://jap.physiology.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=10484570|journal=Journal of Applied Physiology|volume=87|issue=3|pages=1003\u20138|pmid=10484570}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Aerobics (1968)\n*Run for Your Life: Aerobic Conditioning for Your Heart (1974)\n*The Aerobics Way: New Data on the World's Most Popular Exercise Program (1978)\n*The New Aerobics (1979)\n*Aerobics for Women (1982)\n*The Aerobics Program for Total Well-being: Exercise, Diet, Emotional Balance (1982, 1983)\n*Fitness for Life, 6 Audio Cassettes (1983)\n*Aerobics Program (1985)\n*Running Without Fear (1986)\n*The New Aerobics for Women (1988)\n*Preventing Osteoporosis: Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper's Preventive Medicine Program (1989)\n*Controlling Cholesterol: Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper's Preventative Medicine Program (1989)\n*Reducing Cholesterol: A Heart-Smart Guide to Low-Fat Eating (No Nonsense Health Guide) (1989)\n*Overcoming Hypertension: Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper's Preventive Medicine Program (1990)\n*Kid Fitness: a Complete Shape-up Program From Birth Through High School (1991)\n*Dr. Kenneth H. Cooper's Antioxidant Revolution (1994)\n*Its Better To Believe (1995)\n*Faith-based Fitness The Medical Program That Uses Spiritual Motivation To Achieve Maximum Health And *Add Years To Your Life (1997)\n*Antioxidant Revolution (1997)\n*Can Stress Heal? Converting A Major Health Hazard Into A Surprising Health Benefit (1998)\n*Advanced Nutritional Therapies (1998)\n*Regaining the Power of Youth at Any Age (1998)\n*Discoveries (1999)\n*Controlling Cholesterol the Natural Way Eat Your Way to Better Health With New Breakthrough Food\n*Matters of the Heart: Adventures in Sports Medicine (2007)\n*Start Strong, Finish Strong (2007)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Aerobics]]\n*[[Bill Orban]]\n*[[Exercise]]\n*[[Exercise physiology]]\n*[[Training effect]]\n*[[Physical fitness]]\n* [[Power walking]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cooperaerobics.com/ Cooper Aerobics Center]\n*[http://www.cooperaerobics.com/About/Our-Leaders/Kenneth-H-Cooper,-MD,-MPH.aspx/ Kenneth H. Cooper Biography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Kenneth H}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American military doctors]]\n[[Category:American Christian writers]]\n[[Category:American exercise and fitness writers]]\n[[Category:Exercise instructors]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n", "name_user": "109.118.93.72", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenneth_H._Cooper"}
{"title_page": "1930 United States Senate election in New Jersey", "text_new": "{{Infobox Election\n| election_name = 1930 United States Senate elections in New Jersey\n| country = New Jersey\n| flag_year = 1908\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1924 United States Senate election in New Jersey\n| previous_year = 1924\n| next_election = 1932 United States Senate special election in New Jersey\n| next_year = 1932 (special)\n| election_date = November 4, 1930\n| image1 = [[File:Dwight Morrow.jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1 = '''[[Dwight Morrow]]'''\n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1 = '''601,497'''\n| percentage1 = '''58.50%'''\n| image2 = [[File:3x4.svg|x150px]]\n| nominee2 = [[Alexander Simpson (politician)|Alexander Simpson]]\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2 = 401,007\n| percentage2 = 39.00%\n| title = Senator\n| before_election = [[David Baird Jr.]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Dwight Morrow]]\n| after_party = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsNJ}}\nThe '''United States Senate elections of 1930 in New Jersey''' was held on November 4, 1930. \n\n[[Walter Evans Edge]], the Senator elected in 1924, resigned in 1929 to take office as Governor of New Jersey. Interim appointee [[David Baird Jr.]] chose not to seek re-election and Republican [[Dwight Morrow]] won a landslide victory to succeed him.\n\nMorrow also won [[1930 United States Senate special election in New Jersey|a special election held the same day]] for the remaining month of Edge's six-year term, defeating Democrat Thelma Parkinson. Morrow would only serve for ten months before his death in October 1931.\n\n==Candidates==\n*Esther Hill Elfreth (National Prohibition)\n*Henry Jager (Socialist)\n*Dozier Will Graham (Communist)\n*Alexander Kudlik (Socialist Labor)\n*[[Dwight Morrow]] (Republican), U.S. Ambassador to Mexico\n*[[Alexander Simpson (politician)|Alexander Simpson]] (Democrat), State Senator\n\n==General election==\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin no change\n | title=United States Senate election in New Jersey, 1930\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1930&fips=34&f=0&off=3&elect=0&minper=0|title=1930 Senatorial General Election Results - New Jersey}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/1930election.pdf|title=Statistics of the Congressional Election of November 4, 1930|publisher=Clerk of the United States House of Representatives|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Republican Party (United States)\n | candidate  = [[Dwight W. Morrow]]\n | votes      = 601,497\n | percentage = 58.50%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n | candidate  = Alexander Simpson\n | votes      = 401,007\n | percentage = 39.00%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Prohibition Party (United States)\n | candidate  = Esther Hill Elfeth\n | votes      = 18,903\n | percentage = 1.84%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Socialist Party USA\n | candidate  = Henry Jager\n | votes      = 4,519\n | percentage = 0.44%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Communist Party USA\n | candidate  = Dozier W. Graham\n | votes      = 1,627\n | percentage = 0.16%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Socialist Labor Party of America\n | candidate  = Alexander Kudlik\n | votes      = 670\n | percentage = 0.07%\n}}\n{{Election box majority no change\n | votes      = 200,490\n | percentage = 19.50%\n}}\n{{Election box turnout no change\n | votes      = 1,028,223\n | percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n | winner     = Republican Party (United States)\n | loser      = \n | swing      = \n}